INSERT INTO `objects` VALUES (57,1,'2015-02-20 22:30:16','2015-02-20 22:30:28',NULL,'James Richards',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,'2015-01-31 00:00:00','2015-03-22 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,'','Kunstverein München presents James Richards\' first public institutional survey show in Germany. The exhibition brings together a selection of recent video works, as well as collages of moving image and a curated film programme. In conjunction they create a visual and sonic \'curve\' through the Kunstverein\'s four interconnecting gallery spaces.\r\n\r\nWorking across video, sound and installation, Richards’ artistic practice embodies the role of curator, editor and archivist. He uses found, borrowed and self generated material as an expressive and highly personal form of collage. Richards\' often channels other artistic voices through his work too, such as those of Julia Heyward, Stuart Marshall, Stephen Sutcliffe, Michael Curran and Stuart Baker whose films he has curated into his installation.\r\n\r\nRichards is often considered as belonging to a generation of artists who work under conditions determined by an increasingly digitalized dissemination of artistic practice, in which the storage, recall and reworking of information is continuous and fluid. Accordingly, his work posesses a certain contingent and improvised quality, wherby materials are collected over time and re-assembled for different pieces, contexts or audiences.','');
INSERT INTO `objects` VALUES (69,1,'2015-02-23 18:30:34','2015-02-23 20:08:00',NULL,'You and they, 2008',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Duncan Campbell','In his film- and video works Duncan Campbell creates portraits of people and social milieus, which testify to the complex correlation of reality and fiction. Loosely combined resource material from film- and photo archives as well as on-screen animations fuse documentary with fictive moments and build the background on which to question not only the documented subject but also the „documentary gaze“ itself.\r\n\r\nOn the occasion of his solo show at Kunstverein München, Duncan Campbell produced the limited silkscreen “You and they.” A photographic image from the “Community Visual Image” archive that Campbell also used for his film „Falls Burns Malone Fiddels“ provides the basis for this print. \r\n\r\nDuncan Campbell (*1972 in Dublin, Irland) lives and works in Glasgow.\r\n\r\nSolo Exhibitions (selection): MUMOK, Vienna, 2009; Ludlow 38, New York, 2009; ICA, London, 2008; ART Statements, Art Basel 38, Basel, 2008; Hotel Gallery, London, 2008; Lux at Lounge, London, 2006; TART Contemporary, San Francisco, 2005.','Silkscreen on photograph, 48 × 60 cm\r\nEdition: 6 + 1 AP signed and numbered\r\n\r\n€ 1675,–\r\n€ 1425,– For Members');
INSERT INTO `objects` VALUES (78,1,'2015-02-23 20:09:08','2015-02-23 20:09:08',NULL,'Bez nÃ¡zvu (Ohne Titel), 2007',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Cyril Blažo','<p>Neben Künstlern wie Roman Ondák, Boris Ondreiãka und Denisa Lehocká zählt Cyril Blažo zu einer jüngeren Generation von post-konzeptualistisch orientierten Künstlern, welche in den letzten Jahren die aufstrebende slowakische Szene prägten. Sein Interesse gilt dem unendlichen Reichtum medial zirkulierender Bilder, die in seinem Werk über unterschiedlichste Strategien und Techniken in neuen, ironisch pointierten Formulierungen rekonfiguriert werden. Blažo verfolgt so eine Mikropolitik der minimalen ästhetischen Intervention, die den stereotypen Prägungen kapitalistischer Bildökonomien den ethischen Freiraum des lachenden Dritten abtrotzen. Für den Kunstverein München legt Blažo seinen Kniefall vor der sakralen Architektur eines Bankautomaten im postkommunistischen Bratislava als limitierten Siebdruck auf.</p>\r\n<p>Cyril Blažo (*1970 in Bratislava, Slovakei) lebt und arbeitet in Bratislava.</p>\r\n<p>Einzelausstellungen (Auswahl): Kunstverein München, 2007; tranzit.sk, Bratislava, Slowakei, 2006; BOL RAZ JEDEN/KRÁL‘OVSTVO NIČNEROBENIA, Galerie G 99 Brno, Tschechische Republik, 2002; Ateliér Noon, Prag, 1999; Les Enfants Terribles episode No 2, Havlíčkova 20, Bratislava, 1994</p>','Siebdruck, 40,2 × 29,7 cm\r\nAuflage 100 + 10 AP signiert & nummeriert\r\n\r\n€ 290,–\r\n€ 250,– für Mitglieder');
INSERT INTO `objects` VALUES (70,1,'2015-02-23 18:30:34','2015-02-23 18:30:34',NULL,'Kunstausstellung!, 2005 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Jeremy Deller','<p>Working at the intersection of the roles of the artist, the curator and the producer, Jeremy Deller has been creating a broad spectrum of projects that make use of such diverse media as, for instance, installation, film, video, posters and performance. Deller is interested in the creative practices of the everyday which are articulated outside the institutionalised spaces of art and its industries. He playfully transgresses the borders between ‘high’ and ‘low’ cultures thus repeatedly questioning the social function of cultural processes of recognition. For his first comprehensive survey show at Kunstverein München, Jeremy Deller created a limited edition exhibition poster, which was produced with an old printing technique by a workshop in San Francisco that has been specialising in posters for boxing matches for decades.</p>\r\n<p>Jeremy Deller (*1960 in London) lives and works in London.</p>\r\n<p>Solo Exhibitions (selection): Palais de Tokyo, Paris, 2008/09; Aspen Art Museum, Aspen, 2008; Mercer Union, Toronto, 2006; Kunstverein München, München, 2005; Folk Archive, Barbican Art Gallery, London &amp; Kunsthalle Basel, 2005; Gavin Brown’s Enterprise, New York 2004; Art:Concept, Paris, 2002.<br /><br /><br /></p>','Letterpress print (red or rainbow), 55,5 × 35,5 cm\r\nEdition: 2 × 10 signed and numbered on back\r\n\r\n€ 420,–\r\n€ 360,– for members');
INSERT INTO `objects` VALUES (71,1,'2015-02-23 18:30:34','2015-02-23 18:30:34',NULL,'Kiosk Progressions, 2008',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Liam Gillick','<p>Liam Gillick’s work represents an ongoing study of surfaces, structures and systems, that shape our economies of perception through corporate engineering. Across a broad spectrum of media and formats, Gillick creates spaces of potentiality that negotiate our contemporary environments on the borderlines between fiction, utopia and social reality. On the occasion of his touring retrospective “Three Perspectives and a Short Scenario*”, Liam Gillick produced the limited edition “Kiosk Progressions” exclusively for Kunstverein München. Over the course of altogether ten unique archival prints, the geometric figure of a possible space is transformed until it vanishes in a palimpsest of graphic notations.</p>\r\n<p>Liam Gillick (*1964 in Aylesbury, England) lives and works in London and New York.</p>\r\n<p>Solo Exhibitions (selection): Palais de Tokyo, Paris, 2005; ICA, London, 2005; “Project”, Museum of Modern Art, New York, 2003; The Power Plant, Toronto, 2002; Whitechapel Gallery, London, 1999; Frankfurter Kunstverein, Frankfurt, 1999; Villa Arson, Nizza, 1998; Kunstverein Hamburg, 1998; Le Consortium, Dijon, 1997.<br /><br /><br /></p>','Unique Archival Inkjet Print on Acid Free Paper, 30,5 × 22,9 cm\r\nEdition: 10 unique prints signed and numbered\r\n\r\n€ 3.600,–\r\n€ 3.000,– for members');
INSERT INTO `objects` VALUES (72,1,'2015-02-23 18:30:34','2015-02-23 20:04:06',NULL,'Damageplan, 8 December 2004 (â€¦), 2007 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Scott King','Scott King began his professional career as a graphic designer: in the 90s he worked as an art director for the style magazines ID and Sleazenation and designed record covers for pop icons such as the Pet Shop Boys, Morrissey and Suicide. The viral strategies of a parasitic aesthetic already evident in his early commercial work, still dominate his artistic work today. In the traditions of Situationist image politics and the graphic legacy of punk, King amalgamates the circulating signs of consumer culture into bastardised icons that celebrate the disease of their own origins. The Kunstverein’s exclusive edition ‘Damageplan’ translates the Texan thrash metal band’s performance on 8th December 2004 at the Alrosa Villa in Columbus, Ohio into the ‘cool’ cartography of a social diagramme.\r\n\r\nScott King (*1969 in Goole, England) lives and works in London.\r\n\r\nSolo Exhibitions (selection): The Penultimate Straw, Herald St, London, 2008; The Trial Continues Bortolami, New York, 2008; Marxist Disco (cancelled), Kunstverein München, 2008; Oh! Pylon Heaven, Galleria Sonia Rosso, Turin, 2006; Information, Bortolami Dayan, New York, 2006; Scott King, White Columns, New York, 2005.','Silkscreen, 59,4 × 42 cm \r\nEdition: 100 + 20 AP signed and numbered\r\n\r\n€ 240,–\r\n€ 200,– for members');
INSERT INTO `objects` VALUES (73,1,'2015-02-23 18:30:34','2015-02-23 20:03:11',NULL,'BORA BORA Structure for Munich, 2010',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Tobias Madison mit Kaspar Müller and Rebecca Senn','€ 3000,–\r\n€ 2700,– for members\r\nSold Out\r\n\r\nTobias Madison (*1985 in Basel) lives and works in Basel and Zurich.\r\n\r\nSolo Exhibitions (selection): Haus Konstruktiv, Zürich, 2010; Frame, Frieze Art Fair, London, 2010; Do It To Do It, Kunstverein München, 2010; That Leaf! That Mushroom! That Palm Tree! (with Ida Ekblad), Karma International, Zürich, 2010; Hydrate + Perform / Yes I Can! The Movie: A Preview, Swiss Institute, NYC, 2010; Yes I Can!, Cardenas Bellanger, Paris, 2009.','Swing (made out of bamboo and climbing ropes)\r\nLength: 6m \r\nEdition: 3 signed and numbered\r\n\r\nsold out');
INSERT INTO `objects` VALUES (74,1,'2015-02-23 18:30:34','2015-02-23 20:07:11',NULL,'The Impostor, 2007',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Tom Burr','The works by American artist Tom Burr take on the minimalist vocabulary of the 60s and 70s in order to infect them with the ‘dirty facts’ of a lived life. In a detour through abstraction’s historical languages, Burr negotiates the suppressed psychopathologies of the everyday as a critique of recent art history’s ‘unworldly’ aesthetic sediments. For the exhibition “Oh Girl, It’s a Boy!” at Kunstverein München in 2007, Tom Burr created the edition “The Imposter”: a total of 71 signed originals that each consist of a different page from the American original edition of Jean Cocteau’s novel “Thomas, the Imposter” (1925).\r\n\r\nTom Burr (*1963 in New Haven, Connecticut) lives and works in New York.\r\n\r\nSolo Exhibitions (selection): Addict-Love, Sculpture Center, New York, 2008; Secession, Wien, 2007; Swiss Institute, New York (mit Walter Pfeiffer), 2007; Extrospective: Works 1994 – 2006, Tom Burr, Musée Cantonal des Beaux Arts, Lausanne, 2006; Deep Purple, Whitney Museum of American Art, New York, 2000.','Collage, 28 × 35,7 cm \r\nBook page on cardboard\r\nEdition: 71 originals signed and numbered\r\n\r\n€ 360,–\r\n€ 300,– for members');
INSERT INTO `objects` VALUES (75,1,'2015-02-23 18:30:34','2015-02-23 20:04:55',NULL,'Edition Kunstverein MÃ¼nchen II, 2009',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Wolfgang Tillmans','€ 2.380,–\r\nSold Out\r\n\r\nWolfgang Tillmans took the photo for this edition during a trip to Munich. It shows a fragmentary detail of the interior of a friend’s apartment. As in many of his works, Tillmans captures with a sensible and exploratory view, intimate living environments and situations of his closest friends. The pretended triviality of the motif in combination with its silent aesthetics can be read as a cross relevance to the litte and beautiful things in life.\r\n\r\n\r\nWolfgang Tillmans (*1968, Remscheid) lives and works in Berlin and London.\r\n\r\nSolo exhibitions (selection): Hamburger Bahnhof, Berlin, 2008; Kunstverein München, Munich, 2007; Galerie Daniel Buchholz, Cologne, 2007; Pinakothek der Moderne, Munich, 2007; Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago, 2006; PS1 Contemporary Art Center /Moma, New York, 2006; Louisiana Museum for Moderne Kunst, Humlebæk, Denmark 2003; Tate Britain, London, 2003.','C-Print, 49,8 × 41,6 cm\r\nAuflage: 15 + 5 AP signed and numbered on back\r\n\r\nsold out');
